# Include Tests in Plans

When creating or updating implementation plans, include tests wherever they add meaningful coverage. Do not defer testing to a vague follow-up or omit it unless the user explicitly says not to test.

## Per-section coverage

For each plan section that introduces behavior, add a matching test subsection:

| Section | Include tests for |
| --- | --- |
| Models | field persistence, `__str__`, ordering, defaults, custom methods |
| Admin | registration, changelist/add pages load, create/edit via admin when relevant |
| Views / URLs | status codes, context/rendered content, auth/permissions, 404/edge cases |
| Forms / API | valid/invalid input, validation errors, successful submission |
| Templates | cover via view/integration tests using `assertContains` unless template logic is complex |
| Management commands | command output, side effects, idempotency |
| Signals / tasks | triggered behavior and side effects |

Skip tests only when a section has no testable behavior (e.g. pure config scaffolding with no logic).

## Plan structure

- Add a dedicated **Tests** section (or test subsections under each feature section).
- Name test classes/files and list concrete test methods (e.g. `test_detail_view_returns_404_for_missing_post`).
- Add a plan todo for tests when the plan uses todos.
- Include `poetry run python manage.py test <app>` (or the project’s test command) in verification steps.

## Example (Django)

```markdown
## 4. Views — blog/views.py
...

### Tests — BlogPostListViewTests
- test_list_view_returns_200
- test_list_view_shows_post_titles
- test_list_view_returns_404 is N/A here; cover in detail tests
```

Keep tests proportional: cover real behavior, not trivial getters or framework defaults.
